            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'en'" x-cloak>
                <h2>Start with the Conclusion</h2>
<p>There's no universal formula for store advertising budget allocation, but there are underlying principles worth following. The core approach: concentrate budget on creative testing during the learning phase, dynamically allocate based on channel performance during growth, and maximize ROI during maturity.</p>
<p>Sounds like common sense? But the specific ratios and execution methods are where most sellers struggle.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Principle 1: Testing Phase – Spend Where It Counts</h2>
<p>A common mistake among new store owners is spreading budget thin across multiple platforms simultaneously—$50/day on Google, Meta, and TikTok each, hoping something will work.</p>
<p>The reality: all three platforms stay in the learning phase, data samples remain insufficient, and none delivers results. Budget evaporates without meaningful insights.</p>
<p><strong>The right approach: pick 1-2 primary channels and concentrate budget on creative testing.</strong></p>
<p>Take a tool-based store as an example: during cold launch, they allocated 70% of testing budget to Meta. The reasoning was straightforward—clear audience targeting, large reach, and fast feedback on creative iterations. Within two weeks of testing, they identified a creative with 2.5% CTR, then began scaling across channels.</p>
<p><strong>Testing phase budget allocation reference:</strong></p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Phase</th>
<th>Daily Budget per Channel</th>
<th>Creative Variants</th>
<th>Review Cycle</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Cold Launch</td>
<td>$100-200</td>
<td>3-5 sets</td>
<td>Every 3 days</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Testing &amp; Optimization</td>
<td>$200-500</td>
<td>5-8 sets</td>
<td>Weekly</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>Key point: allocate at least 20% of total budget to testing.</strong> Cutting testing costs means paying higher prices when scaling later.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Principle 2: Growth Phase – Diversify Channels, But With Priorities</h2>
<p>After identifying winning creatives, you enter the growth phase. Budget allocation should shift from "concentrated testing" to "performance-based distribution."</p>
<p>Most sellers swing to extremes: either All-in on one channel for scale or spread themselves across seven platforms without meaningful traction on any.</p>
<p><strong>Recommended growth phase budget framework:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Primary channel: 40-50%</strong> + <strong>Secondary channels: 30-40%</strong> + <strong>New channel testing: 10-20%</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<p>A fast fashion store used this structure: Meta as the main battlefield (45%), Google Shopping as a secondary acquisition channel (30%), TikTok for testing new creatives and younger demographics (20%), and 5% reserved for experimental platforms like Pinterest or Snapchat.</p>
<p>This ratio isn't fixed—adjust based on each channel's CPA (Cost Per Acquisition) and ROAS (Return on Ad Spend). Weekly channel performance reviews are essential; if a channel's CPA exceeds target by 1.5x for two consecutive weeks, consider reallocating budget.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Principle 3: Maturity Phase – Maximize ROI, Not Just Volume</h2>
<p>At maturity, your store has stable traffic sources and established audience profiles. The goal shifts from "spend the budget" to <strong>generating higher returns on every dollar spent</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Maturity phase optimization directions:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>Increase budget allocation for returning customers</strong><br />
   Retaining existing customers costs far less than acquisition. Mature stores can redirect 20-30% of budget to retargeting—abandoned cart users, high-value past purchasers, and lookalike audiences based on best customers.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Establish creative refresh routines</strong><br />
   Every channel experiences creative fatigue. A home goods store's approach: update primary creatives every 3 weeks, aligning with seasonal promotions and holidays to maintain freshness.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Use paid advertising to amplify organic reach</strong><br />
   Paid ads aren't just direct conversion tools—they also trigger algorithmic distribution. For example, moderate TikTok spend can trigger viral organic reach, creating compounding effects when paired with content marketing.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<hr />
<h2>A Final Reminder: Budget Allocation Is Dynamic</h2>
<p>Budget allocation isn't a one-time decision. <strong>Your category, target market, platform policies, and competitive landscape all evolve—your strategy must evolve too.</strong></p>
<p>Conduct monthly budget reviews, recalibrating ratios based on last month's CPA, ROAS, and channel trends. Don't expect to set it and forget it; dynamic optimization is the normal state for store advertising.</p>
